define("Slider_5_Description2", "<p class=\"content-p sml\" data-swiper-parallax=\"-200\">The most widely used form of dialysis therapy is called hemodialysis. 
 At the center of hemodialysis is a dialysis filter known as a dialyzer, serving as an artificial kidney, it cleanses the patient blood during the treatment. Inside the plastic tube 30 cm long, or about 12 inches the blood flows trough up to 20 000 hair fine fibers, microscopic pores in the fibers, filter out metabolic waste and excess water, which the dialysis fluid than carries away. As the blood cleansing process proceeds inside the dialyzer a dialysis machine pumps the blood, administers anticoagulants and monitors circulation.</p>
                            <p class=\"content-p sml\" data-swiper-parallax=\"-300\"><b class=\"red-text\">A treatment can take from 3 to 6 hours, usually three times a week.
